                                                                                                                                                               Spinners will rule: Murali
    Cape Town: Muttiah Muralidharan said on Thursday that spinners will play a bigger role in the second edition of the Indian Premier League (IPL) after watching the likes of Harbhajan Singh, Shane Warne and others perform over the past few days. 
  
				 ldquo;Harbhajan rsquo;s performance was the first sign that spin could be a factor in this competition. Since then we have seen Shane Warne rip leg breaks like the old days, 
    Daniel Vettori turned a game for Delhi DareDevils and I had a good night against the Royal Challengers, rdquo; Muralidharan wrote on a cricket website.
    Engineer role
    Calcutta: Former India wicketkeeper Farokh Engineer will help Cricket Espana and Madrid Cricket Club catch the spirit of the sport during the International Cricket Council (ICC) rsquo;s centenary year celebrations at Dubai from Sunday. The Catch the Spirit flag has landed in Spain to mark 100 years of international cricket as ICC Europe celebrates a century of international cricket, catching the spirit from Finland to Italy.
    Junior cricket
    Calcutta: Shristi CA beat Barisha CCC by eight wickets in the quarter finals of the NC Kolay (M) junior cricket tournament on Thursday.
    SUMMARISED SCORES
  Barisha CCC 111. Shristi CA 115/2. Shristi CA won by 8 wkts. l Ashoke Malhotra CA 145. Sonarpur SUSA 138/8. Ashoke Malhotra CA won by 7 runs. l P. Sen (M) CCC 102. Sanctoria CCC 103/2. Sanctoria CCC won by 8 wkts. l City AC 177/5. Mainland SCA 161/8. City AC won by 16 runs.
    Yuki advances
    New Delhi: Yuki Bhambri reached his maiden ITF Futures semi final after pulling off an upset 6-4, 6-4 win over eighth seed Rohan Gajjar in the singles competition of the $15,000 event here on Thursday.Apart from Yuki, Vishnu Vardhan also advanced with a 6-2, 7-5 win over third seed Goran Tesic of Montenegro.
    Prakash wins
    New Delhi: Prakash Amritraj upset fourth seed and world No. 109 Vincent Spadea in straight sets to advance to the singles quarter finals of the $50,000 ATP Challenger event in Tallahassee, United States. In doubles, both Prakash and Somdev Dev Varman lost their first round matches with their respective partners.
    Ghei tied 21st
    Jeju Island (Korea): Gaurav Ghei brought home an excellent opening round card, a three-under 69, to lie tied 21st after the opening round of the Ballantine rsquo;s Championship golf tournament here on Thursday. Shiv Kapur and S.S.P. Chowrasia shared the 55th spot. Jyoti Randhawa was tied at the 78th spot, one shot ahead of Digvijay Singh.
